            The Great Chicago Fire of October 1871 killed 300 people, left 90,000 homeless, and destroyed property worth $200 million. Its scale and aftermath remain relevant to today’s cities facing climate vulnerability and disaster recovery challenges[attached_file:10].
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
